==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} ''ēvādite'', from ''[[evado|ēvādō]]'' (I pass over or flee)

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{legal}} A [[legal]] [[declaration]] or [[avowal]] of [[dismissal]]
#* '''1861''', “The State of the Country”, in ''The Methodist Review'', April 1861, [http://books.google.com/books?id=KIxJAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA313&dq=evadite page 313]:
#*: If the formation of new slave states are the condition of union with slaveholders, we are ready to give them a walking paper — ''abite, '''evadite''', festinate''.
# {{rfv-sense}} A [[declaration]] or [[avowal]] of one's own act, to give it [[legal]] [[validity]].
# {{rfv-sense}} A signal used to [[indicate]] [[acknowledgment]], specifically a written thank you note expressing [[gratitude]] for gifts, assistance, or expressions of sympathy.

